In article <strnlghtCn8y08.LsH@netcom.com>,
David Sternlight <david@sternlight.com> wrote:
>In article <SWM.94Mar25134646@grover.cric.com>,
>Steve McDougall <swm@grover.cric.com> wrote:
>>Look, I'm perfectly willing to grant everything you say:
>>
>>1. The NSA is telling the truth.
>>2. There isn't any secret plot.
>>3. Clipper is secure.
>>
>>My concern isn't that the NSA is hiding something from us.
>>My concern is that the NSA will do exactly what it says:
>>
>>Create a situation where the government holds the keys to all
>>civilian cryptography in the US.
>>
>>I think that this is *bad*.  I don't want it to happen.
>
>What could be a fairer and more straightforward statement of the
>anti-Clipper position than that? Nicely done.

	Errr, actually, some of us aren't even quite *perfectly* willing
to grant the above. Also, there are objections not only to the ends that
the NSA appears to seek (as above), but to the political means by which
they are doing so.

